<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFADFFA70C8CFC9AFAF6FB81" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFADFFA70C8CFC9AFAF6FB81" blockId="9.[151,1437,793,1252]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70C8CFC9AFEABFC8D" bold="true" box="[199,322,865,891]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is superficially very similar to 
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70F67FC99FBB8FC8D" box="[812,1105,865,891]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70F67FC99FC5FFC8D" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1881" box="[812,950,865,891]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lecithocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">P. maculata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70F8BFC99FBB8FC8D" authorityName="Park &amp; De Prins" authorityYear="2019" box="[960,1105,865,891]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="natalensis">P. natalensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA708CDFC99FAEEFC8D" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1158,1287,865,891]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oculiella">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA708CDFC99FAEEFC8D" box="[1158,1287,865,891]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. oculiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be distinguished from the species mentioned above by the male genitalia: 1) uncus more clavate distally with rounded apex, but relatively less clavate distally in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70EC7FC51FCFEFC35" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1881" box="[652,791,937,963]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lecithocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70EC7FC51FCFEFC35" box="[652,791,937,963]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, acute distally in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70FA7FC51FB68FC35" authorityName="Park &amp; De Prins" authorityYear="2019" box="[1004,1153,937,963]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="natalensis">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70FA7FC51FB68FC35" box="[1004,1153,937,963]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. natalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and gradually narrowed toward rounded apex in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70DF9FC35FDDFFC11" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[434,566,973,999]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oculiella">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70DF9FC35FDDFFC11" box="[434,566,973,999]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. oculiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 2) two caudal processes of juxta symmetrical, much longer than tegumen, sickle-shaped with pointed apex, but relatively squat, nearly same length as teguman in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70821FC09FB18FBFD" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1881" box="[1130,1265,1009,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lecithocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70821FC09FB18FBFD" box="[1130,1265,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, asymmetrical, left one much longer than right one, relatively squat in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70EB1FBEDFC62FBD9" authorityName="Park &amp; De Prins" authorityYear="2019" box="[762,907,1045,1071]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="natalensis">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70EB1FBEDFC62FBD9" box="[762,907,1045,1071]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. natalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 3) saccus long, sharply narrowed toward basal 1/2, but much wider, gradually narrowed distally in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70E9DFBC1FCB5FBA5" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1881" box="[726,860,1081,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lecithocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70E9DFBC1FCB5FBA5" box="[726,860,1081,1107]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70FDBFBC1FBC9FBA5" authorityName="Park &amp; De Prins" authorityYear="2019" box="[912,1056,1081,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="natalensis">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70FDBFBC1FBC9FBA5" box="[912,1056,1081,1107]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. natalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and much shorter, about 0.5 times in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFADFFA70CFFFBA5FEDCFB81" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[180,309,1117,1143]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Protolychnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oculiella">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70CFFFBA5FEDCFB81" box="[180,309,1117,1143]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">P. oculiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 4) aedeagus narrow and sharply arched in basal 2/5, whereas in the latter, gently arched.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFADFFA70C8CFB7AFBD3FB49" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFADFFA70C8CFB7AFBD3FB49" blockId="9.[151,1437,793,1252]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFADFFA70C8CFB7AFED2FB6D" bold="true" box="[199,315,1153,1179]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species was described from 
<collectingCountry id="F3603AC2FFADFFA70EE6FB7AFCEDFB6D" box="[685,772,1153,1179]" name="Uganda" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Uganda</collectingCountry>
and is herein reported for the first time from 
<collectingCountry id="F3603AC2FFADFFA708B7FB7AFA8FFB6D" box="[1276,1382,1153,1179]" name="Tanzania" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
. The habitus and genitalia of both sexes were recently illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE607A3FFADFFA70F12FB5EFBDFFB49" author="Park, K. - T. &amp; Koo, J. - M." box="[857,1078,1189,1216]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" pagination="269 - 276" refId="ref6566" refString="Park, K. - T. &amp; Koo, J. - M. (2020) Two new species of Protolychnis Meyrick, 1925 (Lepidoptera, Lecithoceridae) from the Afrotropical Region, with a world check-list of the genus. Zootaxa, 4759 (2), 269 - 276. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4759.2.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Park &amp; Koo (2020)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFADFFA70C8CFB32FD33FB12" box="[199,730,1225,1252]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" type="distribution">
